2500|$|I think you're {{a pretty}} smart boy. I may not talk very good, Mister, but I {{know how to}} take care of smart boys. Let me tell you something. Let me tell you a little secret. I hate your guts, you college son-of-a-bitch! You think you're better than I am! You think you're better because you've had {{everything}} handed to you. Let me tell you something, Mister – I've worked since I was ten years old, and all my life I've known you superior bastards. I knew you people when I was a kid in Boston and I worked in eating-places and you ordered me around … [...] "Oh bus-boy! My <b>friend</b> <b>here</b> seems to have thrown up on the table. Clean it up, please!" [...] I started going to sea as a steward and I worked for you then … [...] "Steward, take my magazine out to the deck chair!" [...] … [...] "Steward, I don't like your looks. Please keep out of my way as much as possible!" [...] Well, I took that crap! I took that for years from pimple-faced bastards who weren't good enough to wipe my nose! And now I don't have to take it any more! There's a war on, by God, and I'm the Captain and you can wipe my nose! The worst thing I can do to you is to keep you on this ship! And that's where you're going to stay! Now get out of here.|$|E
2500|$|In a 1785 {{visit to}} her {{earliest}} friend the Hon. Mrs. O'Neill at Shanescastle in Ulster, [...] "Mrs. Siddons formed {{part of the}} Dramatic Amateur Corps in the theatrical festivities which took place at Shanescastle in 1785, in which Lord Edward Fitzgerald, Mr. Charles O'Neill, M.P. for Cloghuakilty, Mr. Hugh O'Neill, of Carlyan, in the Feevagh, Lord Mountjoy," [...] according to Charles Henry O'Neill, grandson of Hugh O'Neill of Carlyan {{in a letter to}} the editor of the Belfast Daily Mercury, 20 August 1856, where Mrs. Siddons is quoted speaking of Mrs. O'Neill in the following terms : – [...] "I have a dear <b>friend</b> <b>here</b> – a woman of universal genious – and, what is more to me, of unlimited generosity and invariable benevolence, who entrusts me to spend what time I have to spare what time I have to spare with her in this kingdom I cannot refuse her gratitude, as well as inclination, has determined me to comply with her request for to say the truth, she has made me what I am. [...] Her approbation and unremitting kindness, when we were both very young indeed, kindled the latest sparks of genius to a flame, which she now gazes on with wonder and delight. [...] Let this not appear like vanity. [...] Recollect what I am, and you will find it proceeds from a better source. [...] She cannot have so much pleasure in seeing the plant she has so kindly cherished in such a thriving state, as I have in seeing the plant she has so kindly cherished in such a thriving state, as I have in seeing her united to a man every way worthy of her, and whose whole life is devoted to her happiness in short, they form a harmony seldom to be met with – their souls are in unison. [...] The end of this history is, that it is impossible to me to go to Lord Harcourt's this summer how I shall excuse myself I know not; but I know everything forbids me refusing to stay with my earliest friend." ...|$|E
